      <!-- Advantages -->
      <div id="advantages" class="bg-white rounded-xl border border-gray-100 shadow-sm p-6 md:p-8 mb-8">
        <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-[#1B3A5C] mb-4">Advantages</h2>
        <p class="text-[#2D2D2D] mb-4">
          Centrifuges offer several benefits over conventional heating and settling of crude oil to separate BS&amp;W. The following is a list of the main advantages of crude oil centrifuges.
        </p>
        <ul class="space-y-4">
          <li class="flex gap-3">
            <span class="text-[#E8A317] font-bold mt-0.5">&#10003;</span>
            <div>
              <strong class="text-[#1B3A5C]">High Throughput:</strong>
              <span class="text-[#2D2D2D]"> Centrifuges exert thousands of times the force of gravity, thereby causing instant separation of crude oil from the bottom sediment and water. Traditional settling works under a single force of gravity and takes much longer.</span>
            </div>
          </li>
          <li class="flex gap-3">
            <span class="text-[#E8A317] font-bold mt-0.5">&#10003;</span>
            <div>
              <strong class="text-[#1B3A5C]">Compact Size:</strong>
              <span class="text-[#2D2D2D]"> Settling tanks have large footprints and therefore require considerable real estate for deployment. Centrifuges are comparatively much smaller to handle the same volume of oil.</span>
            </div>
          </li>
          <li class="flex gap-3">
            <span class="text-[#E8A317] font-bold mt-0.5">&#10003;</span>
            <div>
              <strong class="text-[#1B3A5C]">Energy Efficient:</strong>
              <span class="text-[#2D2D2D]"> Centrifuges process the crude oil continuously. Therefore, they can use inline heating, which heats up only when the oil is separated. Heater treaters heat thousands of barrels of oil which is colossal energy waste.</span>
            </div>
          </li>
          <li class="flex gap-3">
            <span class="text-[#E8A317] font-bold mt-0.5">&#10003;</span>
            <div>
              <strong class="text-[#1B3A5C]">Quick Deployment:</strong>
              <span class="text-[#2D2D2D]"> Compared to tank farms with related permitting and land acquisition, the centrifuge can be deployed in a fraction of the time.</span>
            </div>
          </li>
          <li class="flex gap-3">
            <span class="text-[#E8A317] font-bold mt-0.5">&#10003;</span>
            <div>
              <strong class="text-[#1B3A5C]">Less Capital Expense:</strong>
              <span class="text-[#2D2D2D]"> Considering the cost of land, tankage, permits, and disposal facilities, the cost of heating and settling is far greater than that of a centrifuge system.</span>
            </div>
          </li>
          <li class="flex gap-3">
            <span class="text-[#E8A317] font-bold mt-0.5">&#10003;</span>
            <div>
              <strong class="text-[#1B3A5C]">Reduced Oil Losses:</strong>
              <span class="text-[#2D2D2D]"> It is possible to produce oil with less than 1% BS&amp;W with a centrifuge system with minimal losses. A considerable amount of oil is lost in drained bottoms to achieve similar quality oil.</span>
            </div>
          </li>
          <li class="flex gap-3">
            <span class="text-[#E8A317] font-bold mt-0.5">&#10003;</span>
            <div>
              <strong class="text-[#1B3A5C]">Better Quality Oil:</strong>
              <span class="text-[#2D2D2D]"> The high g-force exerted by centrifuges leads to a much higher quality of crude oil when compared to oil produced by simple gravity settling.</span>
            </div>
          </li>
          <li class="flex gap-3">
            <span class="text-[#E8A317] font-bold mt-0.5">&#10003;</span>
            <div>
              <strong class="text-[#1B3A5C]">Reduced Disposal Costs:</strong>
              <span class="text-[#2D2D2D]"> A centrifuge-produced dry sludge cake (reduced disposal volume) reduces disposal costs. Conventional tank bottoms contain higher amounts of oil and water, leading to larger disposal volumes.</span>
            </div>
          </li>
        </ul>
      </div>

